      "content": "# The Red Balloon\n\n## Logline\nPASCAL finds companionship in an object that behaves like a friend, turning friendship and loyalty transcending conventional boundaries into simple street behavior, object choreography, and public wonder.\n\n## Taglines\n- A city learns to look up.\n- One friend is enough to change the street.\n- Magic follows when called.\n\n## Synopsis\nThe Red Balloon opens with Pascal climbs a lamppost and unties a large red balloon, clutching it triumphantly before running to the bus stop. The film builds from tiny rules and repeated city spaces: where the object can go, who refuses it, who notices it, and how a child's attachment changes the street around him. Scene 1 gives the deck an early production anchor: Pascal climbs a lamppost and unties a large red balloon, clutching it triumphantly before running to the bus stop. The final movement lands on Scene 20: Hundreds of balloons of every color rise from across all of Paris, stream toward Pascal, twist their strings together, and lift him up into the sky for a journey around the world.\n\n## Film Identity\n- **Genre:** Fantasy / Family\n- **Period:** Mid-20th century (1950s Paris)\n- **Tone:** magical tender fable\n- **Core engine:** A lonely boy who finds a magical friend in a red balloon and, after losing it to cruelty, is rewarded by the solidarity of all balloons who carry him on a journey around the world.\n- **Production read:** 14 major locations, 20 scenes, and a craft burden centered on child performance, object behavior, weather, street geography, crowd movement, and invisible rigging/VFX.\n\n## Themes\n**Friendship and loyalty transcending conventional boundaries**\nScene 13 gives this theme a concrete production anchor: Pascal encounters a real little girl who mirrors the painting of a girl with a hoop, and she holds the string of her own balloon — two balloon-children meeting.\n\n**Loneliness and the human need for companionship**\nScene 1 gives this theme a concrete production anchor: Pascal climbs a lamppost and unties a large red balloon, clutching it triumphantly before running to the bus stop.\n\n**Childhood imagination versus adult authority and rules**\nScene 10 gives this theme a concrete production anchor: The balloon attempts to enter the classroom, causing the children to erupt in noise and chaos as the principal attempts and fails to catch it.\n\n**Sacrifice and devotion — the balloon refuses to leave its friend**\nScene 1 gives this theme a concrete production anchor: Pascal climbs a lamppost and unties a large red balloon, clutching it triumphantly before running to the bus stop.\n\n## Scope / Production Read\n- **Scenes:** 20\n- **Locations:** 14\n- **Exterior Scenes:** 16\n- **Night / Continuous Scenes:** 1\n- **VFX / Stunt Scenes:** 15\n- **Hero Props:** 19\n- **Hero prop focus:** red balloon, painting of girl with hoop, burst balloon, hundreds of colored balloons\n- **Complexity:** High scope. Precise practical-magic scope. The deck should foreground object behavior, child performance, street geography, weather, crowd control, and invisible rigging/VFX.",
